hopobject.body: I've lost my bank card dandrene shampoo antiforfora Serving a small community of 9,500, the Graham drew national attention in 1955 when one of its famous patrons, Blondie the Lion, was photographed outside the drive-in in an old automobile in the September issue of Life Magazine. "The feature story and pictures drew lots of attention for the drive-in and was perhaps one of our most publicized events," said owner Pam Scott. Still, with such a small customer base, they've had to be creative to continue operating so long. "We have sponsored Easter egg hunts, Toys for Tots events, hosted car shows, showed World Series games, given away stuffed animals, and had midnight showings all in an effort to keep our doors open as much as possible during the year."
